b. With forsitan (forsan) the future indicative is used instead of the usual subjunctive: 12, 125 forsan Pacuvio breviter slahim 14, 295 forsitan zyma nocte cadet. Another instance would be 1, 150, if with P we should read· dices hie forsimn ; cs. note on this passage.¹

72. Tenses. a. The imperfect is used instead of (1) the perfect: 11, 184 f. quando licebat per totum cessare diem? (2) the pluperfect in the unreal condition of the past : (3.9. 4, 85 si...liceret; 13, 187 accusatori nollet dare. Cf. 7, 69 f.; 8, 263. In all such cases stress is laid on the continu- ance of the action or state involved.²

b. The future is used to denote the ascertainment in fu- ture time of an action which is present z 1, 126 noli vexare, quiescet. Of. Plaut. Pers. 645 llaec erit bono yenere nata ; i.e. ‘you’ll find she comes of good family.' This occurs most frequently in comedy, and is doubtless colloquial.³

c. To denote the ‘universal present' (gnomic) Juvenal emplo3·S, (1) the future: (3.9. 3, 5241 obiter leyet aut scribet vel dormiet intas ; 7, 187 f. res nulla minoris constabit patri qaam filias ; (2) the perfect : eff. 1, 149 omne in praecipiti vitium stetit ; 2, 83 nemo repente fait turpissimus; 10, 7.*

d. The pluperfect is used in the sense of an imperfect or aorist: ey. 10, 271 f. torva canino latravit ricta qaae post banc vixerat uxor ; 15, 15 f. risam fortasse quibasdam mo- verat ; 5, 76 fuerat. This use of the pluperfeet is not un- common in early Latin and in the Augustan and later poets ; examples‚ too, may be found even in the best prose.⁵
